TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$showHint =3;

$wheel_diameterSI = sprintf("%0.2f", random(1,1.2,0.05));
$wheel_rotations  = sprintf("%0.2f", random(2,2.5,0.05));
$wheel_rotationsSI = $wheel_rotations*10**5; 

$wheel_circumferenceSI = ($wheel_diameterSI*pi);
$distanceSI = ($wheel_circumferenceSI*$wheel_rotationsSI);
$distance = $distanceSI*10**-3;

Context() -> texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR
$PAR

<b>If you do not answer this question correctly in $showHint attempts, you can get a hint.</b>

$PAR
$PAR

Semi-trailer trucks have an odometer on one hub of a trailer wheel. The hub is weighted so that it does not rotate, but it contains gears to count the number of wheel revolutionsâ€”it then calculates the distance traveled. If the wheel has a \($wheel_diameterSI\) \(\textrm{m}\) diameter and goes through \($wheel_rotations \times 10^{5}\) revolutions, how many kilometers should the odometer read? 

$PAR
$PAR

\{ans_rule(40)\} \(\textrm{km}\)

$PAR
$PAR

END_TEXT
BEGIN_HINT
What is the circumference of each tire?
END_HINT

Context() -> normalStrings;

ANS(num_cmp("$distance"));


